Using Histograms of Gradients
\bar default
:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\color black
An alternative to the clustering method is to compute a histogram of the
 gradients based on orientation (REFERENCE NEEDED!!!).
 Quantizing the space allows us to split edges according to their orientation,
 where each bin in the histogram represents an edge orientation.
 Each bin then covers an angle of 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{2\pi}{N}$
\end_inset

radians, where 
\emph on
N
\emph default
 is the number of bins.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\color black
Each bin of the histogram is weighed by the magnitude of edges.
 Once the histogram is constructed, peaks in the magnitude will help determine
 the dominant orientation (
\begin_inset Formula $\varPhi$
\end_inset

) of the dune crestlines.
 The approach poses two main problems:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\color black
Determining 
\emph on
N
\emph default
: In practice, a larger value for 
\emph on
N
\emph default
 has shown to provide finer grain resolution which improves dominant orientation
 determination.
 In Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Resuls-of-unnormalized"

\end_inset

 a value of 
\begin_inset Formula $N=18$
\end_inset

 is used
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\color black
The optimal value for 
\emph on
N
\emph default
 has not yet been determined, but at first glance, smaller values for 
\emph on
N
\emph default
 will cause issues, while larger values seem to improve results.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\color black
Multiple Peaks: Often, images may have multple peaks in the histogram, but
 only one of the peaks should represents the true dominant orientation of
 crestlines.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\color black
One assumption made is that the bin with the largest value represents the
 orientation of the crestline edges.
 Although this assumption holds for many cases, it is not always the case.
 The Skeleton Coast test image provides a good example of this case in Figure
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Resuls-of-unnormalized"

\end_inset

.
 In this particular case, the are two major peaks in the histogram, where
 the stronger is not the part of the crestline edge group, and the weaker
 one is.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\color black
Choosing the higher peak will cause invalid crestlines to be chosen.
 In order to determine which peak best represents the crestline edge group,
 some normalization can be applied.
 The normalization process begins by computing the mean vector of the gradients
 from the edge image as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\color black
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{\mu}\left\langle \bar{x},\bar{y}\right\rangle =\left\langle \frac{\sum_{i=0}^{P}\delta_{x_{i}}}{P},\frac{\sum_{i=0}^{P}\delta_{y_{i}}}{P}\right\rangle 
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\color black
where 
\emph on
P
\emph default
 is the total number of detected edges from the Canny edge detector, 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{x_{i}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{y_{i}}$
\end_inset

 are the 
\emph on
x
\emph default
 and 
\emph on
y
\emph default
 gradient component of the 
\emph on
i
\emph default
th point.
 The mean orientation is computed from the mean vector as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\color black
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bar{\theta_{\mu}}=\arctan\left(\frac{\mu_{\bar{y}}}{\mu_{\bar{x}}}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\color black
The gradients are then normalized by simply subtracting the mean vector
 from each gradient:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\color black
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dot{\delta}\left(x_{i},y_{i}\right)=\left(\delta_{x_{i}}-\mu_{\bar{x}},\delta_{y_{i}}-\mu_{\bar{y}}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\color black
The normalized orientation 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\theta_{i}}$
\end_inset

 can then be computed:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\color black
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dot{\theta_{i}}=\arctan\left(\frac{\dot{\delta_{y_{i}}}}{\dot{\delta_{x_{i}}}}\right)-\bar{\theta_{\mu}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\color black
To determine which bin the 
\emph on
i
\emph default
th edge point belongs to, we simply calculate 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\lceil \frac{\dot{\theta_{i}}\centerdot N}{2\pi}-0.5\right\rceil $
\end_inset

, and increment that bin by the magnitude of the normalized gradient by
 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{\dot{\delta}_{x_{i}}^{2}+\dot{\delta}_{y_{i}}^{2}}$
\end_inset

.
 In essense, this normalization process removes the uneven skew of the gradients
 in the overall image.
 Removing this skew allows true crestline edges to be fairly compared with
 other stronger edges.
 As shown in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Resuls-of-unnormalized"

\end_inset

, the normalization process softens the stronger dominant edge and enhances
 the true crestline edges.
 This process enables crestlines to be accurately detected in images where
 the valleys of dunes are sharp and contain strong edges
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\color black
The gradient normalization process has not be proven to work for all cases,
 only for the images from the test set.
 There may be cases where the normalization may have the opposite effect
 and remove all true crestline.
 More investigation and sample images are required to determine the effectivenes
s of the normalization.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

